6. ğŸ”„ Different Types of Projects and What Happens

â¸»

ğŸ“¦ Java Projects

If your project contains regular Java code:
	â€¢	Jenkins builds it using Maven (mvn install)
	â€¢	Then it uploads the built files to Nexus (mvn deploy)
	â€¢	But if you clicked â€œbuild manuallyâ€, Jenkins will skip the build and just log the run.

â¸»

ğŸ§© Shared Libraries / ACE Applications

If your project builds integration components (used in messaging systems like ACE):
	1.	Jenkins builds a BAR file (packaged deployable unit).
	2.	It zips the file and uploads it to Nexus.
	3.	If youâ€™re manually running the build, Jenkins skips building and just pulls the latest version from Nexus.
	4.	For ACE apps, Jenkins also adds .properties files for all environments inside the zip.

â¸»

ğŸ“š ITX Projects (IBM Transformation Extender)

These are specialized projects used for data mapping and transformation.
	1.	Jenkins finds all the mapping files (called â€œITX mapsâ€).
	2.	It compiles them using a tool called mcompile.
	3.	Then it zips everything and uploads it to Nexus.
	4.	If run manually, Jenkins skips all that and fetches the last uploaded version.

â¸»

ğŸ§± POM Projects

These are not real projects with code but rather â€œparentâ€ projects that other ones inherit settings from.
	â€¢	Jenkins simply builds and uploads them â€” no extra logic involved.

â¸»

âš™ï¸ Configuration Deployments (e.g., Runtime JARs)

These projects are used to deploy runtime files like JARs needed for the environment.
	â€¢	If auto-triggered, Jenkins:
	â€¢	Builds the project
	â€¢	Collects all JARs
	â€¢	Zips and uploads them
	â€¢	If run manually, Jenkins just fetches the last uploaded version from Nexus.

â¸»

7. ğŸ“¦ Deployment Using B3

B3 is our deployment tool for pushing code to real environments.

â¸»

Step 1: Login to B3
	â€¢	Jenkins logs in to B3 and gets authentication cookies for deployment.

â¸»

Step 2: If Environment is NOT UAT

- Create Packages
	â€¢	Jenkins creates a â€œWork Itemâ€ (WI) in B3 for each component to be deployed.

- Check Package Status
	â€¢	It waits until all deployment packages are ready.

â¸»

Step 3: If the branch is not â€œSTDâ€ or a release branch

- Create Release & Deploy
	â€¢	Jenkins creates a release in B3 and checks if the environment is ready.
	â€¢	It ensures no other deployment is locking the environment.

- Check Release Status
	â€¢	Verifies that all components are deployed successfully.
	â€¢	If any fail, the pipeline fails too.

â¸»

8. ğŸ” Automatic Release Version Creation (When Merging to main)

When you merge to the main branch:
	1.	Jenkins runs mvn release:prepare, which:
	â€¢	Updates all version numbers to the release version.
	â€¢	Commits and creates a Git tag.
	2.	Then it updates to the next development version and commits again.

These changes trigger the pipeline again to process the new version.

